<https://guia-kg.skai.etsisi.upm.es/resource/203000035/2025-26/evaluation> a ns1:EvaluationSystem ;
    ns1:evaluationDescription """The assessment will check whether students have acquired the competences of the subject. Therefore, the assessment in the ordinary and extraordinary sessions will use the same types of assessment techniques.


ORDINARY SESSION: Students will be assessed using the progressive assessment system which will consist of the following activities:

Individual consulting projects: Practical work on data analysis problems with Spark accounting for 75% of the final mark. An additional grade-raising challenge is included, which allows you to add up to one extra point to your final grade.
Final team project: Practical application of the knowledge acquired to a real-world problem, with minimal guiding from the teaching staff.
The total weight of the evaluation activities is 110%. In case the average mark exceeds 10, it will be truncated to 10.


EXTRAORDINARY SESSION: the evaluation of the subject in its extraordinary session will consist of the following activities:

Final individual project: Practical application on Spark of the knowledge acquired to a real-world problem, with minimal guidance from the teaching staff (classroom activity).


Rationale for a 110 % weighting in progressive assessment
In the continuous-assessment pathway, students complete a large number of graded tasks. While this variety provides ongoing feedback and encourages steady engagement, it also increases the statistical likelihood that even an outstanding student will lose a few points on one component?perhaps through a minor error, illness, or timetable clash. Under a strict 100 % cap, those small deductions can prevent high-performing students from demonstrating the same level of excellence (a full 10/10) that they could achieve through the single final-exam route.
To restore parity, the progressive scheme includes one additional, low-stakes enrichment activity worth 10 % of the course mark. The cumulative weighting therefore totals 110 %, but the final recorded mark is still capped at 100 %. This extra opportunity serves two purposes:
Fairness: It compensates for the greater exposure to random losses inherent in multiple assessments, ensuring that continuous-assessment students are not disadvantaged compared with those opting for a single exam.
Excellence and motivation: It rewards sustained effort and allows truly exceptional students to offset minor slips and still attain the maximum grade.
In short, the extra 10 % balances the rigor of progressive evaluation with equitable access to top grades."""@es .

